This code, which is obviously bogus, unfortunately causes Rust to give an error message pertaining to associated types, even though it uses none:

````
struct A {}

impl A {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        A {}
    }
}

struct B {}

fn main() {
    B::A::new(); // should be A::new()
}
````

Error:
````
error[E0223]: ambiguous associated type
  --> src/main.rs:13:5
   |
13 |     B::A::new();
   |     ^^^^^^^^^ help: use fully-qualified syntax: `<B as Trait>::A`
````

The error message is particularly confusing because it suggests specifying a trait, but there are no traits in the above code. Of course, the actual code I was debugging (as opposed to the minimal example above) DID use traits, so it took me a little while to figure out what was going on.
